<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition of VHDL

**VHDL** stands for **VHSIC Hardware Description Language**, where VHSIC itself means **Very High Speed Integrated Circuit**. It is a standardized, strongly-typed, hardware description language used to model, simulate, synthesize, and document digital systems at multiple levels of abstraction — behavioral, dataflow, and structural.

In the context of the **KTU 2024 Scheme (PCEVT402 - Digital System Design)**, VHDL is the primary Hardware Description Language taught for translating circuit schematics (combinational and sequential) into textual code that an EDA (Electronic Design Automation) tool can compile into actual gate-level silicon.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Definition:** *VHDL is a formal language used to describe the structure, function, and timing of digital electronic systems. It is an IEEE standard (IEEE Std 1076) that allows both simulation and synthesis of digital hardware.*

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The "Architect's Blueprint"

Imagine you are an **architect** designing a house.

- A **schematic diagram** is the architect's rough sketch on graph paper.
- **VHDL is the formal, written engineering specification** that the contractor (the FPGA/ASIC tool) reads line-by-line to construct the house exactly to design.
- The **Entity** is the *outer wall and door/window positions* — it tells the outside world what inputs and outputs exist.
- The **Architecture** is the *interior blueprint* — it tells how the rooms (logic) are connected and what happens inside.
- **Signals** are the *wires* (electrical copper paths) connecting rooms.
- **Processes** are the *construction workers* that react whenever an input (a sensor) changes.

So, just as an architect's text specification is unambiguous and machine-readable, **VHDL provides an unambiguous, machine-readable description of any digital circuit**.

### 1.3 What is a "VHDL Construct"?

A **VHDL construct** is any syntactically valid language element used to express hardware. These include:
- **Library declarations** (`ieee`, `std`, `work`)
- **Entity declaration** (I/O port description)
- **Architecture body** (the design itself)
- **Concurrent statements** (`when-else`, `with-select`, `<=`, `AND`, `OR`)
- **Sequential statements** (inside `process`: `if-then-else`, `case`, `wait`)
- **Component instantiations** (structural description)
- **Configuration** (binding entities to architectures)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** *Students must master three modeling styles:*
> 1. **Dataflow modeling** (concurrent signal assignments)
> 2. **Behavioral modeling** (process statements)
> 3. **Structural modeling** (component instantiation)
> *All three are examinable in ESE and ESE Module-level assessments.*

### 1.4 Combinational vs Sequential Circuits — Quick Primer

| Feature | Combinational Circuit | Sequential Circuit |
|---|---|---|
| Memory | **No** memory element | **Has** memory (flip-flops) |
| Output depends on | **Present inputs only** | **Present inputs + past history** |
| Feedback loop | Absent | Present |
| Example | Multiplexer, Adder, Decoder | Flip-flop, Counter, Register |
| VHDL process sensitivity list | All inputs | `clk` and `rst` (asynchronous) |

> [!TIP]
> **Exam Tip:** A VHDL code that lacks a `process` or uses only concurrent `<=` statements is **almost certainly combinational**. A VHDL code that uses a `process` triggered by `clk`/`clk'event` is **sequential**.

---

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Anatomy of a VHDL Program — Hierarchical Breakdown

Every complete VHDL design file follows this canonical hierarchy:

$$
\boxed{\text{Entity Declaration} \;\supset\; \text{Architecture Body} \;\supset\; \text{(Process / Components / Concurrent Assignments)}}
$$

#### 2.1.1 Library and Package Declarations

Before declaring any entity, we must import pre-defined logic and arithmetic functions:

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;
USE ieee.numeric_std.all;
```

- `ieee.std_logic_1164` provides the **9-value logic system** (`'0'`, `'1'`, `'X'`, `'Z'`, `'U'`, `'W'`, `'L'`, `'H'`, `'-'`).
- `ieee.numeric_std` provides **signed/unsigned** types and arithmetic functions (`+`, `-`, multiplication, comparison).

#### 2.1.2 Entity Declaration

The entity defines the **interface** of the circuit — its inputs and outputs.

```vhdl
ENTITY mux2to1 IS
    PORT ( a, b : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           sel  : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           y    : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END mux2to1;
```

- `IN` → input port (driver is outside).
- `OUT` → output port (driver is inside the architecture).
- `INOUT` / `BUFFER` → bidirectional / feedback (avoid `BUFFER` in KTU answers).

#### 2.1.3 Architecture Body

The architecture contains the actual logic. Three common styles are:

| Style | Construct Used | Execution | KTU Frequency |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Dataflow** | Concurrent `<=`, `with-select`, `when-else` | Parallel | High |
| **Behavioral** | `process`, `if-then-else`, `case` | Sequential within process | Very High |
| **Structural** | `component`, `port map` | Parallel | Medium |

### 2.2 Operators and Data Types — The Building Blocks

#### 2.2.1 Predefined Data Types

| Type | Values | Use |
|---|---|---|
| `STD_LOGIC` | `'0'`, `'1'`, `'X'`, `'Z'`, `'U'`, etc. | Single-bit logic |
| `STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(n DOWNTO 0)` | Array of `STD_LOGIC` | Bus of width n+1 |
| `INTEGER` | Whole numbers (range-restricted) | Counters, indices |
| `BOOLEAN` | `TRUE`, `FALSE` | Conditional triggers |
| `BIT` | `'0'`, `'1'` only | Legacy, avoid in KTU |
| `UNSIGNED` / `SIGNED` | `numeric_std` library | Arithmetic on vectors |

#### 2.2.2 Logical and Arithmetic Operators

**Logical operators** (operate bitwise on vectors, or scalar on `STD_LOGIC`):

$$
\mathtt{NOT}, \;\mathtt{AND}, \;\mathtt{OR}, \;\mathtt{NAND}, \;\mathtt{NOR}, \;\mathtt{XOR}, \;\mathtt{XNOR}
$$

**Arithmetic operators** (require `numeric_std`):
$$
+, \;\;-, \;\;*, \;\;/, \;\;\bmod, \;\;\rem
$$

**Relational operators:**
$$
=,\; /=,\; <,\; >,\; \le,\; \ge
$$

**Concatenation and slicing:**
$$
\&\; (\text{concatenate}),\quad (n\;\mathtt{DOWNTO}\; m) \;\text{(slice)}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Pitfall:** A common mistake is writing `if sel = "1"` for a 1-bit signal. The correct comparison is `if sel = '1'` (single quotes for scalar, double quotes for vector literals).

### 2.3 Concurrent vs Sequential Statements — The Two Worlds

This is the **single most important distinction** in VHDL.

#### Concurrent Statements (Dataflow)

- Execute **in parallel** (hardware is inherently parallel).
- Used outside `process`.
- Order of writing does **not** affect execution.
- Examples: concurrent `<=`, `when-else`, `with-select`.

```vhdl
y <= a AND b;
z <= c OR d;
```
Both lines are evaluated simultaneously, just like two logic gates.

#### Sequential Statements (Inside `process`)

- Execute **in order**, top-to-bottom, like software.
- Used **only inside a `process` block**.
- The `process` itself is a concurrent statement, but its **internals** are sequential.
- Examples: `if-then-else`, `case-when`, `for-loop`, `while-loop`, `wait`.

```vhdl
PROCESS (a, b, c)
BEGIN
    IF (a = '1') THEN
        y <= b;
    ELSE
        y <= c;
    END IF;
END PROCESS;
```

### 2.4 The Sensitivity List — Critical Concept

The **sensitivity list** in a `process` declares which signals trigger the process. When **any** signal in the list changes, the process executes once from top to bottom.

```vhdl
PROCESS (clk, rst)   -- Sensitivity list
BEGIN
    ...
END PROCESS;
```

- For **combinational processes**: include **all inputs** read inside.
- For **sequential (clocked) processes**: include `clk` and asynchronous `rst` only.

> [!WARNING]
> **Synthesis Tool Warning:** Omitting a signal from the sensitivity list will cause **simulation/synthesis mismatch**. A KTU examiner will deduct marks if a combinational process's sensitivity list is incomplete.

### 2.5 Conditional and Selected Signal Assignments

#### 2.5.1 `WHEN-ELSE` (Concurrent Conditional)

```vhdl
y <= a WHEN sel = "00" ELSE
     b WHEN sel = "01" ELSE
     c WHEN sel = "10" ELSE
     d;
```

#### 2.5.2 `WITH-SELECT` (Concurrent Selected)

```vhdl
WITH sel SELECT
    y <= a WHEN "00",
         b WHEN "01",
         c WHEN "10",
         d WHEN OTHERS;
```

> `OTHERS` is **mandatory** in `with-select` for synthesis completeness.

### 2.6 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Equation / Rule | Application |
|---|---|---|
| Boolean output (MUX 2:1) | $y = \bar{s}\cdot a + s\cdot b$ | Dataflow assignment |
| Full adder sum | $S = A \oplus B \oplus C_{in}$ | Arithmetic VHDL |
| Full adder carry | $C_{out} = (A \cdot B) + (C_{in} \cdot (A \oplus B))$ | Arithmetic VHDL |
| D-flip-flop behavior | $Q_{next} = D$ | Sequential process |
| JK flip-flop behavior | $Q_{next} = J\bar{Q} + \bar{K}Q$ | Sequential process |
| T flip-flop behavior | $Q_{next} = T \oplus Q$ | Sequential process |
| Clock event | `clk'EVENT AND clk = '1'` | Rising edge detection |
| 4-bit counter modulus | $N_{mod} = 2^{n} = 2^{4} = 16$ | State count |
| VHDL concatenation | `signal s : STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(7 DOWNTO 0);` | Bus creation |
| Range definition | `(n DOWNTO 0)` means $n+1$ bits | Vector width |

### 2.7 Engineering Utility

VHDL codes form the foundation of:
- **FPGA prototyping** (Xilinx, Altera/Intel, Lattice).
- **ASIC design** (Application Specific Integrated Circuits).
- **Digital signal processing (DSP)** chips.
- **Embedded systems** with custom peripherals.
- **Aerospace & defense** fault-tolerant circuits (radiation-hardened FPGAs described in VHDL).

---

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step VHDL Codes for Combinational and Sequential Circuits

This section is the **heart of KTU Module 4**. Every code is given line-by-line with full logical commentary. Three modeling styles are demonstrated for **combinational** and **sequential** circuits.

### 3.1 VHDL Code — 2-to-1 Multiplexer (Combinational)

#### 3.1.1 Dataflow Style

```vhdl
-- 2-to-1 Multiplexer in Dataflow Modeling
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY mux2to1 IS
    PORT ( a, b  : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           sel   : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           y     : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END mux2to1;

ARCHITECTURE dataflow OF mux2to1 IS
BEGIN
    y <= a WHEN sel = '0' ELSE
         b;
END dataflow;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `LIBRARY ieee;` — Loads the IEEE library of standard packages.
- `USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;` — Imports all declarations from the 9-value logic package.
- `ENTITY mux2to1 IS ... END mux2to1;` — Defines a black-box called `mux2to1` with three inputs (`a`, `b`, `sel`) and one output (`y`).
- `ARCHITECTURE dataflow OF mux2to1 IS BEGIN ... END dataflow;` — Begins the design body labeled `dataflow` for entity `mux2to1`.
- `y <= a WHEN sel = '0' ELSE b;` — **Concurrent conditional assignment**: when `sel='0'`, output `a`; else output `b`. This compiles directly to a 2:1 mux hardware.

#### 3.1.2 Behavioral Style

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY mux2to1_b IS
    PORT ( a, b  : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           sel   : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           y     : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END mux2to1_b;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF mux2to1_b IS
BEGIN
    PROCESS (a, b, sel)
    BEGIN
        IF sel = '0' THEN
            y <= a;
        ELSE
            y <= b;
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `PROCESS (a, b, sel)` — Declares a process sensitive to all three inputs. Any change re-triggers evaluation.
- `IF sel = '0' THEN` — Sequential conditional inside the process.
- `y <= a;` — Signal assignment. Note: this is a **non-blocking** or **blocking** assignment depending on whether `<=` is used inside process. Inside a process, `<=` is treated as a scheduled update; it becomes effective when the process suspends.
- `END PROCESS;` — Closes the process block.

> [!TIP]
> **KTU Exam Tip:** Inside a `process`, prefer `<=` (signal assignment) over `:=` (variable assignment) for synthesized outputs.

### 3.2 VHDL Code — 4-to-1 Multiplexer (Combinational)

#### 3.2.1 Dataflow with `WITH-SELECT`

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY mux4to1 IS
    PORT ( d     : IN  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0);
           sel   : IN  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(1 DOWNTO 0);
           y     : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END mux4to1;

ARCHITECTURE dataflow OF mux4to1 IS
BEGIN
    WITH sel SELECT
        y <= d(0) WHEN "00",
             d(1) WHEN "01",
             d(2) WHEN "10",
             d(3) WHEN OTHERS;
END dataflow;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `d : IN STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0)` — Declares a 4-bit bus where `d(0)` is the MSB? No — `DOWNTO` here makes `d(3)` the MSB and `d(0)` the LSB. Reading: `(3 DOWNTO 0)` means indices descend from 3 to 0, so d(3) is leftmost.
- `sel : IN STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(1 DOWNTO 0)` — A 2-bit selector bus.
- `WITH sel SELECT` — Evaluates `sel` and assigns `y` based on the case.
- `d(0) WHEN "00"` — When `sel = "00"`, `y` takes `d(0)`.
- `WHEN OTHERS` — Catches all remaining cases (`"11"` and any `'X'`, `'Z'` values).

#### 3.2.2 Behavioral Style with `CASE`

```vhdl
ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF mux4to1 IS
BEGIN
    PROCESS (d, sel)
    BEGIN
        CASE sel IS
            WHEN "00" => y <= d(0);
            WHEN "01" => y <= d(1);
            WHEN "10" => y <= d(2);
            WHEN OTHERS => y <= d(3);
        END CASE;
    END PROCESS;
END behavioral;
```

### 3.3 VHDL Code — 3-to-8 Decoder (Combinational)

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY decoder3to8 IS
    PORT ( a   : IN  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(2 DOWNTO 0);
           en  : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           y   : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(7 DOWNTO 0));
END decoder3to8;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF decoder3to8 IS
BEGIN
    PROCESS (a, en)
    BEGIN
        IF en = '1' THEN
            CASE a IS
                WHEN "000" => y <= "00000001";
                WHEN "001" => y <= "00000010";
                WHEN "010" => y <= "00000100";
                WHEN "011" => y <= "00001000";
                WHEN "100" => y <= "00010000";
                WHEN "101" => y <= "00100000";
                WHEN "110" => y <= "01000000";
                WHEN OTHERS => y <= "10000000";
            END CASE;
        ELSE
            y <= (OTHERS => '0');
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `y : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(7 DOWNTO 0)` — 8-bit output bus.
- `IF en = '1' THEN` — Active-high enable.
- `WHEN "000" => y <= "00000001";` — When input is `"000"`, output bit `0` is asserted.
- `y <= (OTHERS => '0');` — Aggregated assignment: every bit of `y` is set to `'0'`. Equivalent to `y <= "00000000";` but scalable.

### 3.4 VHDL Code — 8-to-3 Priority Encoder (Combinational)

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY prio_encoder_8to3 IS
    PORT ( d   : IN  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(7 DOWNTO 0);
           y   : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(2 DOWNTO 0);
           vld : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END prio_encoder_8to3;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF prio_encoder_8to3 IS
BEGIN
    PROCESS (d)
    BEGIN
        IF d(7) = '1' THEN
            y <= "111"; vld <= '1';
        ELSIF d(6) = '1' THEN
            y <= "110"; vld <= '1';
        ELSIF d(5) = '1' THEN
            y <= "101"; vld <= '1';
        ELSIF d(4) = '1' THEN
            y <= "100"; vld <= '1';
        ELSIF d(3) = '1' THEN
            y <= "011"; vld <= '1';
        ELSIF d(2) = '1' THEN
            y <= "010"; vld <= '1';
        ELSIF d(1) = '1' THEN
            y <= "001"; vld <= '1';
        ELSIF d(0) = '1' THEN
            y <= "000"; vld <= '1';
        ELSE
            y <= "000"; vld <= '0';
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- Priority is given to the **highest-indexed** input first (`d(7)` has highest priority).
- `ELSIF` chains conditions top-down — only the first true branch executes.
- `vld` indicates whether any input is asserted.

### 3.5 VHDL Code — 4-bit Ripple Carry Adder (Combinational)

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;
USE ieee.numeric_std.all;

ENTITY rca_4bit IS
    PORT ( a, b  : IN  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0);
           cin   : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           sum   : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0);
           cout  : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END rca_4bit;

ARCHITECTURE dataflow OF rca_4bit IS
    SIGNAL a_u, b_u, sum_u : UNSIGNED(3 DOWNTO 0);
    SIGNAL cin_u, cout_u   : UNSIGNED(0 DOWNTO 0);
    SIGNAL full_res        : UNSIGNED(4 DOWNTO 0);
BEGIN
    a_u    <= UNSIGNED(a);
    b_u    <= UNSIGNED(b);
    cin_u  <= ("0" => cin);  -- convert scalar to 1-bit unsigned
    full_res <= ('0' & a_u) + ('0' & b_u) + cin_u;
    sum     <= STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(sum_u);
    sum_u   <= full_res(3 DOWNTO 0);
    cout    <= full_res(4);
    cout_u  <= full_res(4);
END dataflow;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `USE ieee.numeric_std.all;` — Required for `UNSIGNED` and arithmetic.
- `SIGNAL ... : UNSIGNED(3 DOWNTO 0);` — Internal signals for arithmetic operations.
- `a_u <= UNSIGNED(a);` — Type conversion from `STD_LOGIC_VECTOR` to `UNSIGNED`.
- `('0' & a_u)` — Zero-extends `a_u` from 4 bits to 5 bits, so the sum never overflows internally.
- `full_res <= ('0' & a_u) + ('0' & b_u) + cin_u;` — Single concurrent assignment using vector addition. The synthesis tool infers an adder chain.
- `STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(sum_u);` — Converts back to standard logic type for the output port.

### 3.6 VHDL Code — D Flip-Flop (Sequential)

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY d_ff IS
    PORT ( d, clk, rst : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           q, qb        : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END d_ff;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF d_ff IS
BEGIN
    PROCESS (clk, rst)
    BEGIN
        IF rst = '1' THEN
            q  <= '0';
            qb <= '1';
        ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1' THEN
            q  <= d;
            qb <= NOT d;
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `PROCESS (clk, rst)` — Asynchronous reset: both `clk` and `rst` are in the sensitivity list, so the process triggers on changes in either.
- `IF rst = '1' THEN` — Highest priority: reset overrides the clock.
- `ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1'` — Detects the **rising edge** of the clock. `clk'EVENT` is true when `clk` just changed, and `clk = '1'` confirms it went high.
- `q <= d;` — On rising edge, D is latched to Q.
- `qb <= NOT d;` — Complementary output updated simultaneously.

> [!NOTE]
> **Modern Alternative (IEEE 1076.2008):** `RISING_EDGE(clk)` can be used in place of `clk'EVENT AND clk = '1'`. KTU 2024 accepts both, but the long form is more portable.

### 3.7 VHDL Code — 4-bit Synchronous Up-Counter (Sequential)

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;
USE ieee.numeric_std.all;

ENTITY counter_4bit IS
    PORT ( clk, rst, en : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           q             : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0));
END counter_4bit;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF counter_4bit IS
    SIGNAL count : UNSIGNED(3 DOWNTO 0) := "0000";
BEGIN
    PROCESS (clk, rst)
    BEGIN
        IF rst = '1' THEN
            count <= "0000";
        ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1' THEN
            IF en = '1' THEN
                count <= count + 1;
            END IF;
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;
    q <= STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(count);
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `SIGNAL count : UNSIGNED(3 DOWNTO 0) := "0000";` — Internal signal declared in the architecture's declarative region. Initialized to zero (synthesis tool may or may not honor the initial value; FPGAs use it for power-on).
- `IF rst = '1'` — Asynchronous, active-high reset.
- `ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1'` — Synchronous behavior on rising edge.
- `IF en = '1' THEN count <= count + 1;` — Synchronous enable: counter increments only when `en` is asserted.
- `q <= STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(count);` — Concurrent output assignment of the internal signal.

### 3.8 VHDL Code — 3-bit Ring Counter (Sequential)

A ring counter cycles a single `'1'` through a shift register:

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY ring_counter_3bit IS
    PORT ( clk, rst : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           q         : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(2 DOWNTO 0));
END ring_counter_3bit;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF ring_counter_3bit IS
    SIGNAL r : STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(2 DOWNTO 0) := "001";
BEGIN
    PROCESS (clk, rst)
    BEGIN
        IF rst = '1' THEN
            r <= "001";
        ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1' THEN
            r <= r(1 DOWNTO 0) & r(2);  -- rotate right
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;
    q <= r;
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `r <= r(1 DOWNTO 0) & r(2);` — Concatenation of bits: lower two bits followed by the MSB. This creates a right-rotation. If `r = "100"`, next `r = "001" & '1' = "011"`? Let us re-check: `r(1 DOWNTO 0)` = `"00"`, `r(2)` = `'1'`, so concatenated = `"001"`. Yes, the bit at index 2 wraps around to index 0. This is rotation.
- `:= "001"` — Initial value gives the "ring" a starting position.

### 3.9 VHDL Code — Moore FSM (Sequence Detector "101") (Sequential)

This is a **classic KTU 14-mark problem**. A Moore machine that detects overlapping sequence `101`:

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY moore_101 IS
    PORT ( clk, rst, din : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           dout           : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END moore_101;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF moore_101 IS
    TYPE state_t IS (S0, S1, S2, S3);
    SIGNAL ps, ns : state_t;
BEGIN
    -- State register
    PROCESS (clk, rst)
    BEGIN
        IF rst = '1' THEN
            ps <= S0;
        ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1' THEN
            ps <= ns;
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;

    -- Next-state logic
    PROCESS (ps, din)
    BEGIN
        CASE ps IS
            WHEN S0 =>
                IF din = '1' THEN ns <= S1; ELSE ns <= S0; END IF;
            WHEN S1 =>
                IF din = '0' THEN ns <= S2; ELSE ns <= S1; END IF;
            WHEN S2 =>
                IF din = '1' THEN ns <= S3; ELSE ns <= S0; END IF;
            WHEN S3 =>
                IF din = '1' THEN ns <= S1; ELSE ns <= S2; END IF;
        END CASE;
    END PROCESS;

    -- Output logic (Moore: depends only on ps)
    PROCESS (ps)
    BEGIN
        CASE ps IS
            WHEN S3 => dout <= '1';
            WHEN OTHERS => dout <= '0';
        END CASE;
    END PROCESS;
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `TYPE state_t IS (S0, S1, S2, S3);` — Enumerated type with 4 symbolic states. Synthesis tool will encode them (binary, one-hot, etc.).
- Two concurrent `PROCESS` blocks: one for state register, one for next-state logic, one for output.
- Moore output depends **only on the present state**, not on `din`. Hence the third process has only `ps` in its sensitivity list.
- Overlap: from S3, if `din = '1'`, transition to S1 (start of a new "101" detection).

### 3.10 VHDL Code — Mealy FSM (Sequence Detector "101") (Sequential)

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY mealy_101 IS
    PORT ( clk, rst, din : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           dout           : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END mealy_101;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF mealy_101 IS
    TYPE state_t IS (S0, S1, S2);
    SIGNAL ps, ns : state_t;
BEGIN
    PROCESS (clk, rst)
    BEGIN
        IF rst = '1' THEN
            ps <= S0;
        ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1' THEN
            ps <= ns;
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;

    PROCESS (ps, din)
    BEGIN
        CASE ps IS
            WHEN S0 =>
                IF din = '1' THEN ns <= S1; ELSE ns <= S0; END IF;
                dout <= '0';
            WHEN S1 =>
                IF din = '0' THEN ns <= S2; ELSE ns <= S1; END IF;
                dout <= '0';
            WHEN S2 =>
                IF din = '1' THEN
                    ns <= S0; dout <= '1';
                ELSE
                    ns <= S0; dout <= '0';
                END IF;
        END CASE;
    END PROCESS;
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- Mealy output depends on both `ps` and `din` — assigned inside the next-state process.
- Only 3 states (Mealy needs fewer states than Moore for the same functionality).
- `dout <= '1'` is asserted when `ps = S2` AND `din = '1'` — a combination not visible until the same clock edge.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Mealy vs Moore Trade-off:**
> - Mealy: fewer states, faster response, output can glitch if input is asynchronous.
> - Moore: more states, output is glitch-free (always synchronized to clock), one-cycle delay.

### 3.11 VHDL Code — 4-bit Register with Parallel Load (Sequential)

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY reg_4bit IS
    PORT ( d    : IN  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0);
           clk, load, rst : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           q    : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0));
END reg_4bit;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF reg_4bit IS
    SIGNAL r : STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0) := "0000";
BEGIN
    PROCESS (clk, rst)
    BEGIN
        IF rst = '1' THEN
            r <= "0000";
        ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1' THEN
            IF load = '1' THEN
                r <= d;
            END IF;
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;
    q <= r;
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- A register is essentially a bank of D-flip-flops sharing a common clock.
- `IF load = '1'` — Synchronous load control. When `load='0'`, the register holds its value (no `else` clause means the old value persists).
- The `:= "0000"` initialization is for simulation only; on FPGA, the power-on value is undefined.

### 3.12 VHDL Code — Universal Shift Register (Sequential)

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY usr_4bit IS
    PORT ( clk, rst : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           sin_l, sin_r : IN STD_LOGIC;
           mode : IN STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(1 DOWNTO 0);
           d    : IN  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0);
           q    : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0));
END usr_4bit;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF usr_4bit IS
    SIGNAL r : STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0) := "0000";
BEGIN
    PROCESS (clk, rst)
    BEGIN
        IF rst = '1' THEN
            r <= "0000";
        ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1' THEN
            CASE mode IS
                WHEN "00" => r <= r;                                -- Hold
                WHEN "01" => r <= r(2 DOWNTO 0) & sin_l;           -- Shift left
                WHEN "10" => r <= sin_r & r(3 DOWNTO 1);           -- Shift right
                WHEN OTHERS => r <= d;                             -- Parallel load
            END CASE;
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;
    q <= r;
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- `r(2 DOWNTO 0) & sin_l` — Bit-by-bit shift: lower three bits stay, MSB is replaced by left serial input.
- `sin_r & r(3 DOWNTO 1)` — LSB is replaced by right serial input.
- `WHEN OTHERS` captures `"11"` mode and assigns parallel load.

### 3.13 VHDL Code — 4-bit BCD Counter (Sequential)

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;
USE ieee.numeric_std.all;

ENTITY bcd_counter IS
    PORT ( clk, rst, en : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           q             : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0);
           tc            : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END bcd_counter;

ARCHITECTURE behavioral OF bcd_counter IS
    SIGNAL count : UNSIGNED(3 DOWNTO 0) := "0000";
BEGIN
    PROCESS (clk, rst)
    BEGIN
        IF rst = '1' THEN
            count <= "0000";
        ELSIF clk'EVENT AND clk = '1' THEN
            IF en = '1' THEN
                IF count = "1001" THEN
                    count <= "0000";
                    tc    <= '1';
                ELSE
                    count <= count + 1;
                    tc    <= '0';
                END IF;
            END IF;
        END IF;
    END PROCESS;
    q <= STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(count);
END behavioral;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- Counts 0,1,...,9,0,1,... — i.e., counts in BCD.
- `IF count = "1001"` — When the count is 9, next clock rolls it over to 0.
- `tc` is a **terminal count** flag: asserted when the counter wraps around.
- `UNSIGNED` allows direct comparison and addition.

### 3.14 VHDL Code — Structural Style: 4-bit Adder Using 1-bit Full Adder

```vhdl
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY full_adder_1bit IS
    PORT ( a, b, cin : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           sum, cout  : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END full_adder_1bit;

ARCHITECTURE dataflow OF full_adder_1bit IS
BEGIN
    sum  <= a XOR b XOR cin;
    cout <= (a AND b) OR (cin AND (a XOR b));
END dataflow;

-- 4-bit ripple carry adder using 1-bit full adder components
LIBRARY ieee;
USE ieee.std_logic_1164.all;

ENTITY rca_structural IS
    PORT ( a, b : IN  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0);
           cin  : IN  STD_LOGIC;
           sum  : OUT STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(3 DOWNTO 0);
           cout : OUT STD_LOGIC);
END rca_structural;

ARCHITECTURE structural OF rca_structural IS
    SIGNAL c : STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(4 DOWNTO 0);
    COMPONENT full_adder_1bit
        PORT ( a, b, cin : IN  STD_LOGIC;
               sum, cout  : OUT STD_LOGIC);
    END COMPONENT;
BEGIN
    c(0) <= cin;
    FA0 : full_adder_1bit PORT MAP (a(0), b(0), c(0), sum(0), c(1));
    FA1 : full_adder_1bit PORT MAP (a(1), b(1), c(1), sum(1), c(2));
    FA2 : full_adder_1bit PORT MAP (a(2), b(2), c(2), sum(2), c(3));
    FA3 : full_adder_1bit PORT MAP (a(3), b(3), c(3), sum(3), c(4));
    cout <= c(4);
END structural;
```

**Line-by-line analysis:**

- Two entities are defined: a 1-bit full adder and a 4-bit structural adder.
- `SIGNAL c : STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(4 DOWNTO 0);` — Internal carry chain of 5 signals (initial carry in + 4 intermediate + final carry out).
- `COMPONENT full_adder_1bit PORT MAP (...)` — Declares the lower-level entity and instantiates it four times.
- `FA0`, `FA1`, `FA2`, `FA3` are **labels** (mandatory in component instantiation) for the four instances.
- `a(0)` is the **LSB** in this notation (`DOWNTO 0` means index 0 is rightmost).

