## 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

### 4.1 VHDL Program Hierarchy (Top-Level Block Diagram)

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[LIBRARY ieee USE Packages] --> B[ENTITY Declaration]
    B --> C[PORT Definition IN OUT INOUT]
    B --> D[ARCHITECTURE Body]
    D --> E[Declarative Region]
    D --> F[Concurrent Statements Region]
    E --> E1[SIGNAL declarations]
    E --> E2[CONSTANT declarations]
    E --> E3[COMPONENT declarations]
    E --> E4[TYPE declarations]
    F --> F1[Concurrent assignment less than or equal]
    F --> F2[WHEN ELSE]
    F --> F3[WITH SELECT]
    F --> F4[PROCESS block]
    F --> F5[COMPONENT instantiation PORT MAP]
    F4 --> F4a[IF THEN ELSE]
    F4 --> F4b[CASE WHEN]
    F4 --> F4c[FOR LOOP]
    F4 --> F4d[WAIT]
```

**Explanation of the flow:**
- A complete VHDL file begins with library and package imports.
- The `ENTITY` defines the I/O boundary visible to the outside world.
- Inside the `ARCHITECTURE`, two regions exist: a **declarative region** (signals, types, components) and a **statement region** (concurrent statements).
- A `PROCESS` block is itself a concurrent statement, but its **interior** is sequential (procedural).

