## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout**
> 1. **Forgetting `LIBRARY ieee` and `USE` clauses** — KTU examiners deduct **2 marks** if the package declaration is missing, because the type `STD_LOGIC` is undefined without it.
> 2. **Mixing `BIT` and `STD_LOGIC`** — The 2017 KTU paper famously penalized students who used `BIT` (legacy type) instead of `STD_LOGIC`. Always use `STD_LOGIC`.
> 3. **Incomplete sensitivity list in combinational `process`** — A latch will be inferred, costing you **3 marks** in synthesis-style questions.
> 4. **Forgetting `WHEN OTHERS` in `with-select` or `case`** — Synthesis will not complete; examiner deducts **2 marks** for non-synthesizable code.
> 5. **Confusing `:=` (variable) and `<=` (signal) assignment** — In a `process`, prefer `<=`. Using `:=` for outputs is a frequent 14-mark killer.

### 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam — May 2024]**
*List the three modeling styles supported by VHDL. State one distinguishing feature of each.*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

1. **Dataflow Modeling:** Uses concurrent signal assignments (`<=`, `when-else`, `with-select`). It describes how data flows from inputs to outputs through logical expressions. Execution is parallel.

2. **Behavioral Modeling:** Uses `process` statements with sequential constructs (`if-then-else`, `case-when`, `for-loop`). It describes the algorithm/behavior of the circuit rather than its structure. Inside the process, statements execute top-to-bottom.

3. **Structural Modeling:** Uses `component` declarations and `port map` instantiations. It describes a circuit as a hierarchy of lower-level building blocks, similar to a netlist. (1 mark per style with feature = 3 marks)

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**
*What is the difference between a concurrent statement and a sequential statement in VHDL? Give one example of each.*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| Aspect | Concurrent | Sequential |
|---|---|---|
| Execution | All concurrent statements execute in parallel (simultaneously) | Statements inside a `process` execute one after another |
| Location | Outside a `process` | Inside a `process` |
| Order | Order of writing does not matter | Top-to-bottom order matters |
| Example | `y <= a AND b;` | `IF sel = '1' THEN y <= a; END IF;` |

Concurrent statements reflect hardware parallelism; sequential statements reflect algorithmic steps inside an active process. (1.5 marks distinction + 1.5 marks example = 3 marks)

